  "response_text": "**Comprehensive Fitness and Diet Plan**\n\nThis plan is designed to help you achieve overall health and wellness. Before starting any new exercise or diet regimen, please consult with a healthcare professional.\n\n**Goal:** Improve overall fitness, increase energy levels, and promote healthy weight management.\n\n**Diet Plan:**\n\n1. **Hydration:** Drink at least 8-10 glasses of water per day.\n2. **Caloric Intake:** Aim for a daily caloric intake of 1500-2000 calories, depending on your age, sex, weight, and activity level.\n3. **Macronutrient Balance:**\n\t* Carbohydrates: 45-55% of daily calories (whole grains, fruits, vegetables)\n\t* Protein: 25-30% of daily calories (lean meats, fish, eggs, dairy, legumes)\n\t* Fat: 20-25% of daily calories (healthy fats, nuts, seeds)\n4. **Meal Frequency:** Eat 4-6 meals per day, including 3 main meals and 2-3 snacks.\n5. **Food Choices:**\n\t* Whole grains (brown rice, quinoa, whole wheat bread)\n\t* Lean proteins (chicken, fish, turkey, tofu)\n\t* Fresh fruits and vegetables\n\t* Healthy fats (avocado, nuts, seeds)\n\t* Low-fat dairy products\n6. **Avoid:**\n\t* Sugary drinks and foods\n\t* Processed and packaged foods\n\t* Saturated and trans fats\n\t* Excessive salt and sugar\n\n**Sample Meal Plan:**\n\n* Breakfast: Oatmeal with banana, almond milk, and walnuts (300 calories)\n* Snack: Apple slices with peanut butter (150 calories)\n* Lunch: Grilled chicken breast with brown rice and steamed vegetables (400 calories)\n* Snack: Greek yogurt with berries and honey (150 calories)\n* Dinner: Grilled salmon with quinoa and roasted vegetables (500 calories)\n* Snack (optional): Carrot sticks with hummus (100 calories)\n\n**Fitness Plan:**\n\n1. **Cardiovascular Exercise:** Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic exercise per week.\n2. **Resistance Training:** Incorporate strength training exercises 2-3 times per week, targeting all major muscle groups.\n3. **Flexibility and Stretching:** Incorporate stretching exercises 2-3 times per week, focusing on major muscle groups.\n4. **High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT):** Incorporate HIIT workouts 1-2 times per week, using exercises like burpees, jump squats, and mountain climbers.\n\n**Sample Workout Plan:**\n\n* Monday (Chest and Triceps):\n\t+ Warm-up: 5-minute cardio\n\t+ Barbell bench press (3 sets of 8-12 reps)\n\t+ Incline dumbbell press (3 sets of 10-15 reps)\n\t+ Tricep pushdown (3 sets of 12-15 reps)\n\t+ Tricep dips (3 sets of 12-15 reps)\n* Tuesday (Back and Biceps):\n\t+ Warm-up: 5-minute cardio\n\t+ Pull-ups (3 sets of 8-12 reps)\n\t+ Barbell rows (3 sets of 8-12 reps)\n\t+ Dumbbell curls (3 sets of 10-15 reps)\n\t+ Hammer curls (3 sets of 10-15 reps)\n* Wednesday (Rest Day)\n* Thursday (Legs):\n\t+ Warm-up: 5-minute cardio\n\t+ Squats (3 sets of 8-12 reps)\n\t+ Leg press (3 sets of 10-15 reps)\n\t+ Lunges (3 sets of 10-15 reps per leg)\n\t+ Leg extensions (3 sets of 12-15 reps)\n* Friday (Shoulders and Abs):\n\t+ Warm-up: 5-minute cardio\n\t+ Dumbbell shoulder press (3 sets of 8-12 reps)\n\t+ Lateral raises (3 sets of 10-15 reps)\n\t+ Reverse fly (3 sets of 12-15 reps)\n\t+ Plank (3 sets of 30-60 seconds)\n\n**Progress Tracking:**\n\n1. **Weight:** Weigh yourself once a week.\n2. **Body Fat Percentage:** Measure your body fat percentage once a month.\n3. **Workout Log:** Keep a workout log to track your progress and adjust your routine as needed.\n4. **Food Diary:** Keep a food diary to track your eating habits and make adjustments to your diet plan as needed.\n\n**Remember:**\n\n* Consult with a healthcare professional before starting any new exercise or diet regimen.\n* Listen to your body and rest when needed.\n* Stay hydrated and fuel your body with a balanced diet.\n* Be patient and consistent, and you will see results over time.",
